title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message:
I'm getting stuck on this board. It has:
• 3V42
• PPBUS_G3H
• PPVRTC_G3H
• PP5V_S5
• PP3V3_S5
• PP1V05_SUS
• PP3V3_SUS

Does not have:
• PP3V3_S3
• PP5V_S4.
• PM_SLP_S4_L 

I've been getting through these missing SLP boards pretty smoothly lately but this one is getting me. Any help would be appreciated. And let me know if there's other information I left off that would be helpful.

title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message: History of the board, water? Check 5V_S3 for pulses, it may power cycle very quickly.

title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message: Was this a drop or a spill, and if a spill, on what area?

title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message:
I'm assuming you meant 5V_S4 but let me know if I'm wrong. 5V_S4 is completely dead. Stays at 0V.

The board was cleaned before I got it but from what I can tell, it definitely looks like a liquid spill up by the CPU, to the top and right of it. Beyond that, the board looks pretty decent.

title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message: I realize SLP issues are tricky enough when they're right in front of you, let alone across the globe, but do you have any other suggestions for this one?

title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message: Check power to RTC circuit and 32KHz from clock chip

title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message: Is the SMC in the "right" mode, check the SMC_TDI SMC_TDO etc stuff. you can have a green light and still get shit on PM_SLP_S4_L if the SMC is trolling you.

title: No PM_SLP_S4_L on 820-3476
message: What is the right mode the SMC should be in when it is on and working properly?
